msContents.summary: Prayer Book.This fifteenth-century manuscript from Denmark contains religious texts in Danish and Latin of a devotional nature. It also includes two full-page illustrations of Christ.

msItem.title: Passionale
Reflections on the Life of Christ
Betragtninger over Kristi levned
msItem.textLang: The main text in in Old Danish, while the heading is in Latin
msItem.rubric:
Extendit manum et artipuit
gladium vt ymmolaret filium suum Deij
msItem.incipit:
Han vth rakte syn hand
Oc greb swærdh at han
skulde offre syn søn
msItem.explicit:
Thet giørdhe
han til een amminilse hans
hælghæ pinæ oc dødh
msItem.filiation: This part has been copied from Cod. Holm A 31.

msItem.title: Prayers to Maria Magdalena, St Barbara and the Virgin Mary, and some of David's Psalms in Latin
msItem.rubric:
Her byris sancte marie magdalene
tidher thunnæ annar skal lesses
synnerlik oc serlic for alle tidher
msItem.incipit:
Ui bethe theg saligh och
mildhestæ maria magdalena
msItem.explicit:
hilp
megh j alle myne nødh thor
the liketh Amen
msItem.bibl: Nielsen, Middelalderens danske bønnebøger III 44-58 No. 431. Ed. 72. Fols 114r.16-126r:13 IV 343-346 Nos 1075-1078. Fols 126:13-129v

msItem.author: Cistercian monk of the Abbey of Pontigny
msItem.title: Psalterium Beate Marie Virginis
Psalter of the Blessed Virgin Mary
Vor frues psalter
msItem.rubric:
Godhe mænniskæ sighe at thet
hær æfter fylgher kalles vor frw
saltere Oc æræ thar vtj halff
ottende synne tiwghw stykke
Oc hwart there begynnes vpper
Ane thet ær swo møghet at sighe
helset vare thw.
msItem.incipit:
Ave paradysens poort
lyfsens træ Som jak
hafde bort tabet ta
gher nw at worde mik søt weth
thik ok mik voxer helses fruct
msItem.explicit:
jak fonge sættes meth
hælghe mæn j abrahams
skøøth veth samme vor herre
christum Amen
msItem.note: The Psalter was once attributed Bonaventura (Giovanni di Fidanza), but it is now known that it was written by a Cistercian monk of the Abbey of Pontigny, France.
msItem.bibl: Nielsen, Middelalderens danske bønnebøger III 143-145:7 No. 501. Only the first 20 verses [fols 130r-132r:5] are from AM 72 8vo; the text in this edition is otherwise taken from AM 75 8vo

foliation.p: Foliated on upper right-hand corners of the recto pages from 1-148 (including fol. 15bis, which is blank).

collation.p: 13 gatherings of 10 folia each, followed by one of 7 (originally 9) and one of 9 (originally 10) folia. There are catchwords at the end of each gathering (bottom of verso pages).

condition.p: The lower margin, particularly towards the end of the manuscript, has been damaged by damp.

layout.p: The manuscript is written in one column throughout with 18 to 21 lines per page. There are a few coloured initials, mostly red, but some blue and yellow ones do occur. There are also red majuscules in the text. There are a number of headings in red, particularly in the last four gatherings.

handNote.p: Written in one hand throughout in a practised gothic semi-cursive.

decoNote.p: On fol. 147r there is an outline drawing of Christ, sitting naked on a stone, arms crossed, with a large yellow halo.
On fol. 147v there is another drawing of Christ, standing with his hands raised, arms open, wearing a loin cloth, with a large yellow halo.

additions.p:
On the front pastedown Árni Magnússon has written: Ex auctione Birkerodianâ
1709

binding.p: Wooden boards, raised bands, red-dyed calf skin. Iron clasp on the front board. The binding has been restored.

accMat.p: There are two notes from the eighteenth or nineteenth century pasted to fol. 49v explaining the words mullov and kænneswennene.

origin.p: The manuscript was written in Denmark in the fifteenth century.

provenance.p: The codex once belonged to Jacob Bircherod.

acquisition.p: According to Árni Magnússon's note on the front pastedown, the manuscript was purchased at Bircherod's auction in 1709.

source.p: Catalogued 30 August 1999 by EW-J and AWS.
